<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-495-896  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 495 896.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  May 21 1990 n591 p43(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Plastic optical fiber in for the short-haul. (includes relatedarticle titled 'Making the fiber-optic LAN connection')</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bindra, Ashok.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Plastic optical fiber is starting to gain wide acceptance as themedium of choice for short-haul communications.andP;  Plastic opticalfiber cannot compete with glass fibers in long-haulimplementations, but plastic's improved performance along with itslow manufacturing costs make it perfect for many uses.andP;  Plasticoptical fiber will win market share in local area networkapplications according to a market research report that claimswithin three years plastic will become more economical thatunshielded twisted-pair cables or glass fiber.andP;  Plastic ispreferable to glass for some uses because it is more flexible andnot as brittle as glass.andP;  According to market estimates, plasticsales should grow from $53 million in 1989 to $500 million by2000.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsOptical CommunicationsCablesCommunications Equipment.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Plastic optical fiber in for the short-haul. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>